   <abstract>The current study examined (1) the characteristics of the advice networks of six Innovation schools among educators within grade-level PLCs in a city, South Korea, and (2) the extent to which these social network characteristics are related to the outcomes of teacher work, including collective actions, grade-level efficacy, and collective satisfaction. Building on social capital theory and using SNA, this study offered a unique contribution by focusing on teachers' advice and/or information-seeking networks around the discussion of teacher instructional practices. In particular, grade-level teams in six Innovation schools emerged as critical conduits of social capital as to course content, PLC knowledge, and student assessment. Results support the idea that the characteristics of teachers' social relationships at the collective and individual levels may be important elements for nurturing teachers' collective learning and productive outputs. Along with the social connections at work, the role of trust has given credence to the necessity of organizational improvement. This study also found that classroom teachers who occupied leadership roles (grade-level headteachers, academic affairs headteachers, etc.) played an important role in advice networks, but principals and assistant principals did not highly engage in the advice networks. Results indicate that for current Innovation PLC reforms to be successful, there needs to be an understanding of the teacher social networks embedded within professional learning communities. To improve teacher outcomes and eventually student achievement, policymakers and scholars have to highlight the significance of collaborative structures and targeted professional learning opportunities in the school context.</abstract>
